{
  "text": "While the sequence analysis of PAO1 provides scientists with an enormous amount of data on this organism, it is also appreciated that not all P. aeruginosa strains are PAO1. Overall approximately 3% of the DNA is unique between P. aeruginosa clinical isolates and PAO1, a number significantly lower than between E. coli strains [CITATION_1] . Pathogenic isolates of P. aeruginosa can contain an approximately 50 kb region of DNA not present in PAO1. This DNA may be considered a \"pathogenicity island\", which is an unstable region containing genes encoding products important for virulence or survival in specific environmental niches [CITATION_2] . Strain PAO1 contains other DNA in this region [CITATION_3] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "25525965",
